{{Infobox person | name = Ann Twinam | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | alma mater = [[Yale University]] | employer = [[University of Texas at Austin]] | occupation = Historian | title = | salary = | networth = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = }} '''Ann Twinam''' (born Cairo, Illinois 1946) is an American historian of colonial [[Latin America]]. Twinam graduated from [[Northern Illinois University]] in 1968, and earned her Master's (1972) and doctorate (1976) in History from [[Yale University]]. Her dissertation was published as a monograph in 1982 as ''Miners, Merchants, and Farmers in Colonial Colombia'' (University of Texas Press, Austin, Texas, 1982) and in a Spanish translation, ''Comerciantes y Labradores: Las Raíces del Espiritu Empresarial en Antioquia: 1763-1810'' (Fundación Antioqueña para los Estudios Sociales, Medellín, Colombia, 1985). She is a Professor of History at the [[University of Texas at Austin]].<ref name="utaustindepartementbio">{{cite web|title=Ann Twinam|url=https://liberalarts.utexas.edu/history/faculty/at2552|website=Department of History|publisher=The University of Texas at Austin|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> She taught at the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 1974 to 1998, where she received tenure in 1981.<ref name="utaustindepartementbio"/> She won the 2016 [[Beveridge Award]] from the [[American Historical Association]], the Bolton-Johnson Prize from the [[Conference on Latin American History]],<ref>http://clah.h-net.org/?page_id=60 accessed 18 December 2017</ref> the Bryce Wood Book Award from the [[Latin American Studies Association]],<ref>http://lasa.international.pitt.edu/eng/congress/brycewood_history.asp accessed 18 December 2017</ref> and the Bandelier/[[Asunción Lavrin|Lavrin]] Book Prize in Colonial Latin American History from the [[Rocky Mountain Council for Latin American Studies]] (RMCLAS).<ref>https://rmclas.org/bandelierlavrin-award-2/ accessed 18 December 2017</ref> She won the 2000 Thomas F. McGann Book Prize from RMCLAS for ''Public Lives, Private Secrets: Gender, Honor, Sexuality and Illegitimacy in Colonial Spanish America''<ref>Stanford: Stanford University Press 1999.</ref><ref>https://rmclas.org/thomas-mcgann-award/ accessed 18 December 2017</ref> and Honorable Mention in 2001 [[Herbert E. Bolton|Bolton]] Prize from the Conference on Latin American History.<ref>http://clah.h-net.org/?page_id=65 accessed 18 December 2017.</ref> This work was translated to Spanish as ''Vidas públicas, secretos privados: Género, honor, sexualidad e ilegitimidad en la Hispanoamérica colonial'' <ref>(Fondo de Cultura Económica, Buenos Aires 2009)</ref> Twinam was Chair of the Conference on Latin American History (2003–04), the professional organization of historians of Latin America, affiliated with the [[American Historical Association]].<ref>http://clah.h-net.org/?page_id=542 accessed 19 December 2017</ref>
