'''Béla Ferenc József Grünwald de Bártfa''' ({{lang-hu|bártfai Grünwald Béla Ferenc József}}; 2 December 1839 – 4 May 1891) was a Hungarian nationalist politician and historian who was active in [[Upper Hungary]] (today mostly [[Slovakia]]).

==Life and career==
His father was a [[Zipser German]], Augustin Grünwald, while his mother Johanna Majovszky was a noble woman with Polish ancestry.
Born in [[Svätý Anton|Szentantal]], he trained as a lawyer, receiving a degree from the [[Royal University of Pest]]. Serving first as administrator (''[[ispán|alispán]]'') of [[Zólyom County]], in the [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1878|1878 elections]] he was elected a member of the Hungarian [[Országgyűlés|House of Representatives]] for Szliács (modern [[Sliač]]) in that county  as a member of the [[Liberal Party (Hungary)|Liberal Party]]; he subsequently left the Liberals in 1880, serving as an independent before joining the [[Moderate Opposition]] party.{{sfn|Sturm|1888|p=213}} He was an activist for the assimilationist policies of [[Magyarisation]] in the predominantly Slovak region of Upper Hungary, founding and supporting the [[Upper Hungary Magyar Educational Society]].{{sfn|Kirschbaum|2010|p=300}} He viewed the construction of a centralised state as a political priority.{{sfn|Pók|1982|p=24}}

In his book "Közigazgatásunk és a szabadság" (Budapest, 1876) (Our public administration and freedom) he explained his views about the nationalization/Hungarianization policy, he urged the Hungarian politicians to act so effective and inexorable, like the French did in France and English did in the United Kingdom.<ref>Közigazgatásunk és a szabadság" (Budapest, 1876)</ref> 

As a historian, Grünwald became a corresponding member of the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] after the publication of his 1888 work, ''The Old Hungary'' (''A régi Magyarország'').{{sfn|Sturm|1888|p=213}} In his historical works, he pursued a [[People's history|"democratic" method]] of [[historiography]].{{sfn|Lakatos|1910|p=416}} He stated in ''The New Hungary'' (''Az új Magyarország''), the sequel to his 1888 book, "The genius, too, is born. He is born in a particular age, as a member of a particular nation, a class and a family, and the stamp these circles press onto his personality in his youth stays on him even if he has later come into conflict with them."<ref>Quoted in [[#{{harvid|Lakatos|1910}}|Lakatos 1910]], p. 416. "A géniusz is születik. Születik egy bizonyos korban, mint egy nemzet, egy osztály s egy család tagja, s a bélyeg, melyet e körök ifjú korában nyomnak egyéniségére, megmarad rajta még akkor is, ha később ellentétbe jutott vele."</ref> He charged the Hungarian nobility with a lack of national sentiment, and feeling greater solidarity with nobles from other nations than with the Hungarian nation;{{sfn|Benedek|1898|p=310}} the nobles, he argued, had neglected the development of Hungary as a [[nation-state]].{{sfn|Pók|1982|p=24}} Nevertheless, on 22 April 1889, he accepted [[ennoblement]] from [[Emperor Franz Joseph I]], becoming "de Bártfa" (''bártfai'').{{sfn|Lakatos|1910|p=416}}

Grünwald committed suicide by gunshot wound to the head in unclear circumstances while visiting Paris on 4 May 1891.{{sfn|Reszler|1998|p=33}}{{sfn|Lackó|1986|p=14}} Shortly before his suicide, he sent a telegram to [[Albert Apponyi]], the leader of the Moderate Opposition, briefly notifying him of his death: "Béla Grünwald has died after a long period of suffering".<ref>[[#{{harvid|Lackó|1986}}|Lackó 1986]], p. 15. "Grünwald Béla hosszú szenvedés után meghalt."</ref> In his famous dramatic 1929 account, ''The Paris Story'' (''A párizsi regény''),{{sfn|Wilkinson|2009|p=105}} [[Dezső Szomory]] describes Grünwald's death and burial:

{{blockquote|He committed suicide on the bank of the Seine, just next to the water, thinking in one final thought that the water current would take him far away. But the water current didn't hurt him; it only washed the wound on his temple ... Grünwald's burial at [[Montmartre Cemetery]] was yet more dismal. On this autumnal day, [the cemetery] was like an English landscape, with plenty of grey air, some trees, some shrubs ...|Dezső Szomory|''A párizsi regény''<ref>Quoted in [[#{{harvid|Cs. Szabó|1939}}|Cs. Szabó 1939]], p. 45. "A Szajna partján lett öngyilkos, közvetlenül a víz mentén, úgy gondolván egy utolsó gondolatján, a víz sodra el fogja vinni messze. De a víz sodra nem bántotta, csak a sebét mosta el a halántékán ... Még szomorúbb volt Grünwald temetése a Montmartre-temetőben. Olyan volt ez ezen az őszi napon, mint egy angol tájkép, sok szürke levegővel, néhány fával, néhány cserjével ..."</ref>}}

Grünwald's [[epitaph]] reads, "Here lies Béla Grünwald, unbreakable apostle of the Hungarian theory of the state."<ref>[[#{{harvid|Pók|1982}}|Pók 1982]], p. 24. "Itt nyugszik Grünwald Béla, a magyar állameszme törhetetlen apostola."</ref>

