'''Marsyas of [[Philippi]]''' ([[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]]: Μαρσύας, Κριτοφήμου, Φιλιππεύς; 3rd century BC) was a [[Macedon]]ian [[Greeks|Greek]] historian and the son of Critophemus. He was often called ''Marsyas the Younger'' ({{lang-grc-gre|Μαρσύας ὁ Νεώτερος}}) to distinguish him from [[Marsyas of Pella]], with whom he has frequently been confounded. The earliest writers by whom he is cited is [[Pliny the Elder|Plinius]] and [[Athenaeus]]. The latter tells us that he also served as a priest of [[Heracles]]. His works were ''Μακεδονικά'' On Macedonia (6 books), ''Αρχαιολογία'' Archaeology (On Attica?) (12 books) and ''Μυθικά'' On Myths (7 books).
==References== *FGrHist 135/6 (Fragments). *[https://web.archive.org/web/20070903231942/http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/2071.html Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology] by [[William Smith (lexicographer)]] *[https://books.google.com/books?id=uYkixD6-Oh8C&pg=PA302&dq=Marsyas+of+Philippi&sig=GR0oiBQXANdSUS6Bc5xy711ib4A Atthis: The Local Chronicles of Ancient Athens by Felix Jacoby]
