{{other people||Samuel Schmucker (disambiguation)}}
'''Samuel Mosheim Schmucker''' or '''Smucker'''<ref>Smucker changed the spelling of his family name.</ref> (January 12, 1823 – May 12, 1863) was an [[United States|American]] historical writer and popular biographer.
==Biography== Born at [[New Market, Virginia|New Market]], [[Virginia]], the son of respected [[Lutheran]] pastor [[Samuel Simon Schmucker]],<ref>{{Cite book|author=John Walter Wayland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iN8qIyxGfLUC&pg=PA563|title=A History of Shenandoah County|location=Strasburg, Virginia|publisher=Shenandoah Publishing House|year=1969|page=563}}</ref> Samuel Schmucker graduated from [[Phillips Academy]], Andover, Massachusetts, in 1839 and [[Washington & Jefferson College|Washington College]] in [[Pennsylvania]] in 1840 and became a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] pastor in the [[Pennsylvania Ministerium]]. Schmucker held pastorates at [[Lewistown, Pennsylvania|Lewistown]] (1842–45) and Germantown, [[Pennsylvania]] (1845–48).
Schmucker left the ministry in 1848, studied law, and practiced in [[Philadelphia]] (1850–53). After two years in New York, he returned to Philadelphia and devoted his remaining years to writing, mostly popular biographies. According to the [[National Cyclopaedia of American Biography]], Schmucker's works "exhibit diligence in compiling rather than deep research."<ref>''National Cyclopaedia of American Biography'', 5: 101 (1891).</ref>
A fierce critic of the [[Higher Criticism|Higher Critic]] [[David Friedrich Strauss]] and his fellow "Modern Infidels," Schmucker unwittingly anticipated the [[Shakespearean authorship question]] with a mocking demonstration that "historic doubts regarding [[Jesus Christ|Christ]]" were "equally applicable to [[Shakespeare]]." Although he never doubted that Shakespeare had written Shakespeare, the 25-year-old Schmucker "carefully mapped out almost all the arguments subsequently used to question Shakespeare's authorship."<ref>[[James S. Shapiro|James Shapiro]], ''Contested Will: Who Wrote Shakespeare?'' (New York: Simon & Schuster, 2010), 76.</ref>
Schmucker died in Philadelphia on May 12, 1863.<ref>https://archive.org/stream/nationalcyclopae05newy#page/100/mode/2up</ref>
==Publications== *''Historic Doubts Respecting Shakespeare, Illustrating Infidel Objections Against the Bible'' (1848, 1853) *''Court and Reign of [[Catherine II, Empress of Russia]]'' (1855) *''Life of [[John C. Frémont]], with his Explorations'' (1856) *''Life and Times of [[Alexander Hamilton]]'' (1856) *''Life and Times of [[Thomas Jefferson]]'' (1857) *''Arctic Explorations and Discoveries'' (1857) *''The Yankee Slave-Driver'' (1857) *"History of the Mormons" (1857)<ref>https://www.baumanrarebooks.com/rare-books/smucker-samuel/history-of-the-mormons/103250.aspx</ref> *''Life of Dr. [[Elisha Kent Kane]] and Other American Explorers'' (1858) *''Life and Times of [[Henry Clay]]'' (1859) *''Life and Times of [[George Washington]]'' (1860) *''[[Blue law|Blue Laws]] of [[Connecticut]]'' (1860) *''History of the Modern [[Jew]]s'' (1860) *''A History of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in the [[United States]]'' (volume i, 1862)
