{{notability|date=June 2014}}
The month names in [[Turkish language|Turkish]] are derived from three languages: either from Latin, Levantine Arabic (which itself took its names from [[Hebrew and Aramaic]]), or from a genuine Turkish word. The Arabic-Hebrew-Aramaic month names themselves originate in the ancient [[Babylonian calendar]], and are therefore akin to the names of months in the [[Hebrew Calendar]], specifically Shevat, Nisan, Tammuz and Elul. The original Babylonian months were actual lunar months, as the Hebrew months of the same names are to this day, much like months in the Islamic calendar. Turkey has used Gregorian AD year numbering officially since 1926, though Gregorian calendar dates were in use since March 1917. The names of the months from February to September had been used in the now abandoned [[Rumi calendar]], with the other four still retaining their old Arabic/Aramaic names. In 1945, these four received names of Turkish origin.
{| class="wikitable" |- !English !Turkish !Etymology |- |January |ocak |Turkish origin, meaning "oven" or "stove". Literal translation of Arabic word "kānūn".<ref>http://nisanyansozluk.com/?k=k%C3%A2nun&lnk=1</ref> |- |February |şubat |Arabic origin (Šubāṭ), taken from Aramaic |- |March |mart |Latin origin (Martius) |- |April |nisan |Arabic origin (Nīsān), taken from Aramaic |- |May |mayıs |Latin origin (Maius) |- |June |haziran |Arabic origin (Ḥazīrān), taken from Aramaic |- |July |temmuz |Arabic origin (Tammūz), taken from Aramaic |- |August |ağustos |Latin origin (Augustus) |- |September |eylül |Arabic origin (Aylūl), taken from Aramaic |- |October |ekim |Turkish origin, meaning "sowing" (of seeds) |- |November |kasım |Arabic origin word which is meaning "divider".<ref>http://nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kas%C4%B1m&x=0&y=0</ref> This word referring to beginning of winter. According to a Turkish weather proverb winter begins on 8 November. |- |December |aralık |Turkish origin, meaning "gap"<ref>http://nisanyansozluk.com/?k=aral%C4%B1k&x=0&y=0</ref> |}
